<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-261-640  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 261 640.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  March 1990 v7 n3 p32(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>And the wall came tumbling down: Eastern European countries headinto a new age of computing. (includes related article on thechanging computer market in the Soviet Union)</TITLE><AUTHOR>St. Clair, Melanie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer market research analysts forecast major growth in EasternEuropean markets for microcomputers and networks, but thosecountries must develop the political, economic, and marketingenvironments that will support high technology.andP;  There are manypersons in Eastern Europe who can and want to embrace thetechnologies, but there is also a shortage of people to implementand support both software and hardware.andP;  A lack of money inEastern European countries underlies predictions thatcost-effective LANs will be the chosen alternative to moreexpensive minicomputers and mainframes.andP;  US firms will likely beat least six months behind countries not belonging to theCoordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls (CoCom) inexporting microcomputers and LANs to Eastern Europe because of USand CoCom restrictions.andP;  The impacts of the 1992 EuropeanCommunity consolidation are also discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Eastern EuropeMarket AnalysisComputer IndustryEconomics of ComputingOutlookRequirements Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>